  "tacticalAnalysis": {
    "GER": {
      "summary": "Germany's 3-4-3 was relentless from kick-off, with SCHLOTTERBECK and TAH dominating the centre-back role and KIMMICH/BROWN providing constant width as wing-backs. NMECHA's 6th-minute goal set the tone for a night of clinical finishing and high-quality passing (89% completion, 125 line breaks). The front three of WIRTZ, HAVERTZ, and NMECHA/MUSIALA interchanged freely to create mismatches — 4.17 xG on 26 attempts is one of the match's most dominant outputs this tournament.",
      "strengths": [
        "SCHLOTTERBECK's 100% line break completion (22/22) from CB position epitomised Germany's ball-playing quality — defenders were attackers in disguise",
        "MUSIALA's creativity in tight spaces (7 ball progressions, 6 take-ons in limited minutes) showed Germany's elite technical depth even from the bench and in transitions",
        "Clinical set-piece delivery — SCHLOTTERBECK's 38' header from a corner and the penalty conversion showed multi-dimensional goal threat",
        "Team shape was compact in and out of possession — only 8 shots conceded (from CUW), with high defensive line maintained at 50m in highBlock phase"
      ],
      "weaknesses": [
        "HAVERTZ's goal at 87' via deflection inflated the xG difference slightly — some of Germany's 26 attempts lacked the sharp finishing quality the score suggests",
        "Conceded COMENENCIA's deflected goal at 21' when shape was temporarily loose — shows even dominant teams can be caught on an isolated transition",
        "High possession games can mask pressing vulnerabilities — CUW's 339 total pressures found space occasionally (18.09s ball recovery for CUW shows Germany gave up the ball more than expected at times)",
        "The 6 blocked shots suggests Curaçao's low block was effective at limiting direct access — Germany had to wait for set-piece and transition chances to break through cleanly"
      ]
    },
    "CUW": {
      "summary": "Curaçao set up in a 4-1-2-3 designed to absorb and counter, with COMENENCIA as the defensive midfield anchor. COMENENCIA's 21' deflected goal raised brief hopes, but Germany's quality was simply overwhelming — 57.8% possession, 26 shots, 4.17 xG. Curaçao pressed high (339 total pressures) but ball recovery took 18.09s on average, meaning the press was reactive rather than organized. The 4-1-2-3 became a 4-4-2 mid-block for most of the second half.",
      "strengths": [
        "COMENENCIA's goal at 21' showed Curaçao can punish momentary lapses — the deflection was fortunate but the pressing trigger that created it was intentional",
        "COMENENCIA and OBISPO's defensive work rate was excellent — 12 and 8 possession regains respectively, with 5 interceptions for OBISPO (most in match)",
        "High pressing volume (339 pressures) kept Germany on their toes early and prevented complete domination in the first 30 minutes",
        "LEANDRO BACUNA's composure in possession (56 passes at 86%) gave Curaçao structure when they had the ball, preventing complete chaos"
      ],
      "weaknesses": [
        "Only 8 shots and 0.4 xG — Curaçao's 4-1-2-3 offered no real attacking threat after the early goal, with LOCADIA isolated and substituted at 65'",
        "339 pressures with 18.09s ball recovery time exposes poorly coordinated press — high volume but low efficiency; Germany found pockets consistently",
        "The low and mid-block (37% and 25% out-of-possession phases) couldn't handle Germany's width — KIMMICH and BROWN created overloads repeatedly down the flanks",
        "Only 3 crosses attempted (1 completed) and 34 ball progressions show Curaçao had no effective pathway to create chances from their possession spells"
      ]
    }
  },
